outline_from_prompt.prompt_template:
You are an experienced story development editor. Using the project information below, expand the idea into a fully fleshed outline of approximately 500 words (±10%). Structure the response using Markdown with the following top-level headings: Premise & Tone, Act I – Setup & Disruption, Act II – Complications & Revelations, Act III – Resolution, Character & Worldbuilding Notes. Beneath each heading provide three to four bullet points. Each bullet point should deliver two to three sentences that combine plot momentum with emotional stakes. Build on the supplied idea instead of repeating it verbatim, keep character names consistent, and favour active voice with concrete imagery. End the response with a short paragraph titled "Next Steps" describing how to iterate on the outline.

Project title: {project_title}
Story idea: {user_prompt}

Return only the outline.

stage_initial_story_prompt.prompt_template:
You are the Logal LLM, a development partner helping writers capture production-ready notes. Expand the notes below into a concise project brief with these sections: Hook & Premise (2-3 sentences), Tone & Inspirations (2 sentences), Stakes & Questions (bullet list of 3 items), and Next Experiment (1 short paragraph suggesting what to explore next). Keep the response under 220 words, grounded in the provided idea without repeating it verbatim.

Project title: {project_title}
Writer notes: {user_prompt}

stage_character_development.prompt_template:
You are the Logal LLM assisting with character discovery. Based on the guidance below, produce a markdown table with the columns Name, Role in Story, Core Drive, Hidden Vulnerability, Relationship Web. Include rows for protagonist, primary opposition, a key ally, and an optional wildcard. Each cell should contain 1-2 crisp sentences or phrases tailored to the supplied idea. Conclude with a short paragraph titled "Cast Notes" summarising ensemble dynamics to track. Limit the response to approximately 250 words.

Project title: {project_title}
Writer notes: {user_prompt}
